Here is a simple implementation of the Composite Design Pattern in Kotlin. This pattern allows you to treat individual objects and compositions uniformly, meaning that they can be treated as if they are all instances of the same class.

```kotlin
interface UIComponent {
    fun render()
}

class Button(private val label: String) : UIComponent {
    override fun render() = println("Rendering button with label $label")
}

class Panel(private val components: MutableList<UIComponent> = mutableListOf()) : UIComponent {
    fun addComponent(component: UIComponent) = components.add(component)
    fun removeComponent(component: UIComponent) = components.remove(component)

    override fun render() {
        println("Rendering panel")
        components.forEach { it.render() }
    }
}

fun main() {
    val button1 = Button("Button 1")
    val button2 = Button("Button 2")
    val panel = Panel()
    panel.addComponent(button1)
    panel.addComponent(button2)
    panel.render()
}
```
In this example, `UIComponent` is the Component interface and `Panel` is the Composite class. The `Button` class represents leaf objects in the hierarchy. 

The composite pattern allows you to build complex tree structures from simpler components. In this case, a panel can contain multiple buttons or other panels, forming a hierarchical structure. When rendering the panel, it delegates the rendering of its children to them. This way, the client code doesn't need to know whether an object is a simple component or a composite. It just calls `render()` on the top-level component and all child components are rendered as well.

