raw_response:
**SRP Violation**

The SRP (Single Responsibility Principle) states that a class should have only one reason to change, meaning it should have only one job. In the given code, the `DeviceManager` class has multiple responsibilities such as configuring devices, updating firmware, playing media and adjusting volume. This violates the SRP because if we need to make changes in any of these functionalities, we would have to modify the `DeviceManager` class which goes against the principle of single responsibility.

**Solution**

To fix this issue, we can create separate classes for each functionality such as `ConfigurationManager`, `FirmwareUpdater`, `MediaPlayer` and `VolumeAdjuster`. Each of these classes will have a single responsibility and hence adhere to the SRP. 

Here is an example of how you could refactor the code:

```csharp
public class ConfigurationManager
{
    public void ConfigureDevice(IDevice device)
    {
        device.DisplayInfo();
        device.Connect();
    }
}

public class FirmwareUpdater
{
    public void UpdateFirmware(INetworkDevice device, string firmwareVersion)
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Updating firmware for " + device.GetDeviceName());
        device.UpdateFirmware(firmwareVersion);
    }
}

public class MediaPlayer
{
    public void PlayMedia(IMediaDevice device)
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Playing media on " + device.GetDeviceName());
        device.Play();
    }
}

public class VolumeAdjuster
{
    public void AdjustVolume(IMediaDevice device, int level)
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Adjusting volume on " + device.GetDeviceName());
        device.SetVolume(level);
    }
}
```

In this refactored code, each class has a single responsibility and can be modified independently without affecting the others. This makes the code more maintainable and adheres to the SRP.

